{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d094b4ec-32d9-4dd1-8b36-811a6a126af2","content":"Here's the analysis:\n\n**Root Cause:** The project itself is fine — the overhead is architectural. Each `dotnet build` invocation spins up a new MSBuild host process, JITs the build engine, and re-evaluates the project graph from scratch. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server in-process.\n\n**Three fixes, in order of impact:**\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the build host alive and watches for changes — eliminates startup cost entirely:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server (`.NET 7+`)\nSet this environment variable to keep an MSBuild worker process warm between standalone `dotnet build` calls, mirroring how VS works:\n```\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\nThis can be added to a shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`) or a team-shared `Directory.Build.rsp`.\n\n### 3. Add a `Directory.Build.rsp` for team-wide defaults\nThis response file auto-applies flags to every `dotnet build` in the repo:\n```\n# Directory.Build.rsp\n-nodeReuse:true\n```\n`-nodeReuse:true` (the default, but worth being explicit) keeps MSBuild worker nodes alive for 15 minutes between builds for reuse.\n\n---\n\n**Why VS is fast:** Visual Studio hosts MSBuild in-process permanently — it never pays startup or JIT costs after the first build. Options 1 and 2 above replicate that behavior on the CLI. No changes to the `.csproj` are needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc2ab806-90e1-4ac2-9c7c-501cd20f080e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've already verified analyzers aren't the issue and that incremental build targets work correctly. The overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation.\n\nThe key insight here is the difference between how Visual Studio and CLI builds work:\n\n1. **Visual Studio** uses a long-lived MSBuild server process (the \"design-time build\" and build manager), so it doesn't pay the startup cost on each build.\n2. **`dotnet build`** by default starts a new MSBuild process each time, paying the full startup and project evaluation cost.\n\n\nThe main solution is to enable the MSBuild server that's available in .NET 8+, which keeps a persistent out-of-process node between builds. This can be activated either by setting the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable or by adding `<MSBuildServer>true</MSBuildServer>` to the project or Directory.Build.props file, which gives the CLI builds the same performance advantage Visual Studio already has.\n\nFor iterative development, `dotnet watch` is another strong option since it keeps the process alive and does incremental rebuilds without the startup overhead. For larger solutions with multiple projects, the graph-based build flag can also help by evaluating the project graph once rather than repeatedly.\n\nI should verify the exact property names and environment variables—the MSBuild server is controlled via `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`, though I'm less certain about project-level configuration. The core recommendation is really to use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop since it directly addresses the repeated startup cost. 3. I could also set up a `Directory.Build.props` file with optimized build flags to apply across the project.","outputTokens":1360,"requestId":"783D:28F9DD:104FD4:1410A3:69F549F7"},"id":"67f63037-d08a-499e-8b36-c528ea6c9f56","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:49:28.697Z","parentId":"c08b01b1-87d0-4c9d-8638-555ff3263929"}
